gs, with education and its role in politicization, self-determination, and social change, and with the restorative process and the meaning of Native healing.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 26. Apr 2024) 0aConsciousness. 0aIndians of North AmericaxEducationzCanada. 0aIndians of North AmericazCanadaxPolitics and government. 0aIndians of North AmericazCanadaxReligion. 0aIndians of North AmericazCanadaxSocial conditions. 0aIndigenous peopleszCanadaxReligion. 0aIndigenous peopleszCanadaxSocial conditions. 0aOlder IndianszCanada. 7aBIOGRAPHY & AUTOBIOGRAPHY / Native Americans.2bisacsh  aeducation.  afirst nations.  aspirituality.1 aCouture, Ruth, eeditor.4edt4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/edt1 aMcGowan, Virginia, eeditor.4edt4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/edt08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertACUP Complete eBook-Package 2013z978311127412608iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertACUP Upgrade eBook-Package 2013z978311127715840uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9781926836539423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/document/cover/isbn/9781926836539/original  a978-3-11-127412-6  ACUP Complete eBook-Package 2013b2013  a978-3-11-127715-8  ACUP Upgrade eBook-Package 2013b2013  aGBV-deGruyter-alles